CloudFront: caching content close to users.

CloudFront is AWS's content delivery network. The job is to cache content close to the user, so that most requests are answered from the edge instead of being dragged across the internet to the origin. It runs from more than six hundred edge locations in over a hundred cities, with a tier of larger regional edge caches sitting between the edge and the origin to absorb cache misses. Here's a request flow: D-N-S resolves the distribution name to the nearest edge; the edge checks its cache; on a hit, the object is returned immediately; on a miss, the edge fetches from the regional edge cache, then from the origin over the AWS backbone, caching the response on the way back. Beyond caching, CloudFront terminates T-L-S at the edge, brings free Shield Standard DDoS protection and W-A-F integration, and speaks H-T-T-P-two and H-T-T-P-three regardless of what the origin speaks.

An origin is where CloudFront fetches content on a miss: an S3 bucket, an S3 website endpoint, an A-L-B, an E-C-2 instance, or any H-T-T-P server. A single distribution can have multiple origins, with cache behaviours routing different path patterns to each.

For an S3 origin, the recommended pattern is Origin Access Control, or O-A-C. You keep the bucket completely private and let only CloudFront read from it: CloudFront signs its origin requests with Sig-V-four, and the bucket policy allows the CloudFront service principal scoped to that specific distribution. There's no public access and no presigned-U-R-L leakage to worry about. O-A-C replaced the older Origin Access Identity, which still lingers but lacks S-S-E-K-M-S support and the newer regions. Default to O-A-C on every new distribution.
